2026-03-28T09:48:15.963Z JOY-007D item.created "AI instructions use JOY_AUTHOR env var instead of --author flag" [ai:claude@joy delegated-by:horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-28T09:48:22.946Z JOY-007D comment.added "AI agents currently prefix joy commands with JOY_AUTHOR env var (e.g. JOY_AUTHOR="ai:claude@joy" joy close ...). This breaks the shell permission model because the allowed command is "joy", not "JOY_AUTHOR=... joy". Fix: update AI instructions and skill to use --author flag instead (e.g. joy close JOY-0005 --author ai:claude@joy)." [ai:claude@joy delegated-by:horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-28T09:48:24.334Z JOY-006A comment.added "Note: until this item is implemented, AI agents must use --author flag instead of JOY_AUTHOR env var. Using the env var breaks shell permission matching for the joy command. See JOY-007D." [ai:claude@joy delegated-by:horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-28T10:05:32.675Z JOY-0004 comment.added "Closing as wontfix. The acronym is already read-only in project set, preventing accidental changes. If someone manually edits project.yaml, mixed ID prefixes (old and new) coexist without issues -- item lookup is ID-based, not acronym-based. New items get the new prefix, old items keep theirs, and all references (parent, deps) continue to work. The only downside is cosmetic inconsistency, which does not justify the complexity of a full migration (renaming files, rewriting all ID references, updating event log)." [ai:claude@joy delegated-by:horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-28T10:05:43.586Z JOY-0004 item.status_changed "new -> closed" [ai:claude@joy delegated-by:horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-28T10:33:14.936Z JOY-007F item.created "Guard as joy-core module for centralized runtime validation" [ai:claude@joy delegated-by:horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-28T10:33:24.493Z JOY-007F comment.added "Guard is Joy's centralized runtime validation layer (Guardianship pillar of AI Governance). It intercepts all write operations and enforces the Trust Model at execution time.\n\nArchitectural decision: Guard lives as a joy-core::guard module, not as a separate subproject. Rationale:\n- Guard enforces Joy's process model (capabilities, gates, members) -- no Joy, no Guard\n- All consumers (joy-cli, platform/server, app) already depend on joy-core\n- Jot does not need Guard (no capabilities, no AI members, no gates)\n- Judge (separate repo) communicates with Guard via event log format, not shared code\n- Avoids cross-repo coordination overhead with no benefit\n\nDesign principles:\n- Passthrough for simple setups (solo, no AI members) -- zero overhead\n- Progressive activation as members and gates are added (dimmers, not switches)\n- Single validation point for all write operations\n- Produces structured enforcement events in the event log (for Judge to consume)\n\nExisting checks to consolidate into Guard:\n- Gate enforcement (allow_ai, requires_role, requires_ci) -- currently in status command\n- Capability validation -- currently in add/comment commands\n- Member permission checks -- scattered across commands\n\nNew checks Guard enables:\n- Prompt injection resilience (JOY-0011)\n- Budget pre-checks before job start\n- Sandbox enforcement for AI agents\n- Input validation for AI-authored content\n\nADR-021 to be created." [ai:claude@joy delegated-by:horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-28T10:34:37.665Z JOY-007F comment.added "ADR-021 created: docs/dev/adr/ADR-021-guard-as-joy-core-module.md. Covers progressive activation, existing checks to consolidate, new checks enabled, event log integration for Judge, and the conceptual Rust API." [ai:claude@joy delegated-by:horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
2026-03-28T10:34:41.547Z JOY-007F item.status_changed "new -> closed" [ai:claude@joy delegated-by:horst.schwarz@joydev.com]
